\begin_layout Section
Hardness of Volume Estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BF87,BF88"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Suppose there is a deterministic algorithm that takes a convex body 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subset\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 given by a membership oracle and outputs 
\begin_inset Formula $A(K),B(K)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(K)\le\vol(K)\le B(K)$
\end_inset

 and makes at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{a}$
\end_inset

 calls to the membership oracle for 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is some convex body 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 for which
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{B(K)}{A(K)}\ge\left(\frac{cn}{a\log n}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 is an absolute constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will prove the following simpler bound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "E86"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 For any deterministic algorithm that makes 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 queries to a membership oracle for a convex body 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq B^{n}$
\end_inset

 and returns 
\begin_inset Formula $A(K),B(K)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(K)\le\vol(K)\le B(K)$
\end_inset

,
 there is some convex body 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{B(K)}{A(K)}\ge\frac{2^{n}}{m}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words,
 even getting a simple exponential volume approximation requires an exponential number of queries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For all queries 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B^{n},$
\end_inset

the oracle answers YES and for queries outside the unit ball it answers NO.
 After 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 queries 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\ldots,x_{m}$
\end_inset

,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\conv\left\{ x_{1},\ldots,x_{m}\right\} \subseteq K\subseteq B^{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Now by Lemma ,
 the volume of the convex hull of 
\emph on
any 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
points in the unit ball is at most a 
\begin_inset Formula $m/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 fraction of the unit ball's volume.
 This proves the theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\ldots,x_{m}\in B^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vol\left(\conv\left\{ x_{1},\ldots,x_{m}\right\} \right)\le\frac{m}{2^{n}}\vol(B^{n}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 define 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}=B(x_{i},\|x_{i}\|/2)$
\end_inset

,
 a ball with diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x_{i}\|\le1/2$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vol\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{m}B_{i}\right)\le m\cdot\vol(B(0,1/2))=\frac{m}{2^{n}}\vol(B^{n}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We argue that 
\begin_inset Formula $\conv{x_{1},\ldots,x_{m}}\subset\bigcup B_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 be a point not contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 the angle at 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 induced by the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y-x_{i}$
\end_inset

 must be acute,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle y,x_{i}-y\rangle<0
\]

\end_inset

and this holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 In other words,
 the halfspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle y,x-y\rangle<0$
\end_inset

 separates 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 from all the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore it separates it from their convex hull.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computing the volume exactly is hard even for explicit simple polyhedra as the following theorem asserts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DF88"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P={x:x\in[0,1]^{n},a^{\top}x\le b}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is an integer vector.
 Computing the volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 (specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\#$
\end_inset

P-hard.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cutting Plane method for Volume Computation:
 Reduction to Center-of-Gravity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cutting plane method provides a simple algorithm for computing the volume of a bounded set or,
 more generally,
 the integral of a function.
 The algorithm below relies crucially on the ability to compute the center of gravity (or centroid) of the original set/function restricted by halfspaces.
 For simplicity we describe it here for the case when the input object is a convex body.
 This reduction from volume computation to centroid computation is deterministic,
 and hence establishes the hardness of the latter problem.
\end_layout

