\begin_layout Standard
The idea behind the algorithm is simple:
 when we cut a set with a hyperplane through its centroid,
 the line joining the centroids of the two sides passes through the original centroid (see Figure
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
ref{fig:cutting-volume}
\end_layout

\end_inset

);
 moreover,
 the ratio of the two segments is exactly the ratio of the volumes of the two halfspaces (i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{k}=\vol(K^{(0)})/\vol(K^{(k)})$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:centroid"

\end_inset

For any measurable bounded set S in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 and any halfspace 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 with bounding hyperplane containing the centroid of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{centroid}(S)=\frac{\vol(S\cap H)}{\vol(S)}\,\mbox{centroid}(S\cap H)+\frac{\vol(S\cap\overline{H})}{\vol(S)}\,\mbox{centroid}(S\cap\overline{H}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following lemma has a proof similar to that of the Grunbaum theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:width"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a convex body with centroid at the origin.
 Suppose that for some unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|a|\ge\frac{b}{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The goal of this proof is to show that a cone attains the maximum ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $b/|a|$
\end_inset

 (and it equals 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in that case).
 As with the proof of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Grunbaum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is symmetric by replacing each cross section 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\in K\colon\theta^{\top}x=t\}$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-dimensional ball of the same volume with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{n-1}(t)C_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-dimensional volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $K\cap\{y\in\R^{n}:y^{\top}\theta=t\}$
\end_inset

,
 with the center of gravity at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 We will exploit the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 is concave in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 and replace 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 by a line going through 
\begin_inset Formula $(b,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,r(0))$
\end_inset

 so that we get a cone with base at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that the center of gravity of the cone,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 is to the left of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{b}{|a|}\le\frac{b-t_{0}}{t_{0}-a}=\frac{n}{n+1}\frac{n+1}{1}=n
\]

\end_inset

which can be rearranged to give the result.
 The equation for the cone is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(t)=-\frac{r(0)}{b}(x-b).
\]

\end_inset

Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $y(t)\le r(t)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,b]$
\end_inset

 since it is a chord between two points of a concave function and therefore always below the concave function.
 To see why 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)\le y(t)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[-a,0]$
\end_inset

,
 consider 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)=r(t)-y(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(t)=r'(t)-y'(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(0)=r'(0)-y'(0)\ge0$
\end_inset

,
 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $y'(t)$
\end_inset

 is a constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $r'(t)$
\end_inset

 is decreasing,
 we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $r'(t)-y'(t)\ge0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\le0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(0)=0$
\end_inset

 by construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $y(t)$
\end_inset

,
 we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)\le0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\le0$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
t_{0} & =\frac{\int_{a}^{b}ty^{n-1}(t)dt}{\int_{a}^{b}y^{n-1}(t)dt}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\int_{a}^{b}y^{n-1}(t)dt}\left(\int_{a}^{0}ty^{n-1}(t)dt+\int_{0}^{b}ty^{n-1}(t)dt\right)\\
 & \le\frac{1}{\int_{a}^{b}y^{n-1}(t)dt}\left(\int_{a}^{0}tr^{n-1}(t)dt+\int_{0}^{b}tr^{n-1}(t)dt\right)=0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}\le0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the above property,
 we can show that the algorithm reaches a cuboid in a small number of iterations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a convex body in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[-r,r]^{n}\subseteq K\subseteq[-R,R]^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Algorithm 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{CuttingPlaneVolume}$
\end_inset

 correctly computes the volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n\log\frac{nR}{r})$
\end_inset

 centroid computations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Grunbaum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 at each iteration,
 the volume of the remaining set 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 decreases by at least a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\frac{1}{e})$
\end_inset

.
 When the directional width along any axis is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 (namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\max_{x\in K}\left|e_{i}^{\top}x\right|\leq r$
\end_inset

),
 the algorithm stops cutting along that axis.
 So,
 just before the last cut along any axis,
 the width in that direction is at least 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 we use the center of gravity to cut.
 By Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:width"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the directional width along every axis of the surviving set is at least 
\begin_inset Formula $r/(n+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Since the set always contains the origin,
 and the original set contains a cube of side length 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

,
 when the algorithm stops,
 it must be an axis-parallel cuboid with each side of length in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[r/(n+1),r]$
\end_inset

.
 So the final volume is at least 
\begin_inset Formula $(r/(n+1))^{n}.$
\end_inset

 The initial volume is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the number of iterations is at most 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log_{(1-\frac{1}{e})}\left(\frac{(2R)^{n}}{(r/(n+1))^{n}}\right)=O\left(n\log(nR/r)\right).
\]

\end_inset

In each iteration,
 by Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:centroid"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the algorithm maintains the ratio of the volume of the original 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 to the current 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{(k)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

